      "runOutput": "`parseCsvLine` is a very simple helper that turns a single CSV line (a string) into an array of values by splitting on commas.\n\nFrom `parser.js`:\n\n```js\nexport function parseCsvLine(input) {\n  return input.split(\",\");\n}\n```\n\nExplanation:\n\n- It takes one argument, `input`, which is expected to be a string representing one line of CSV, e.g.:\n  ```js\n  \"a,b,c\"\n  ```\n- It calls `input.split(\",\")`, which:\n  - Looks for every comma `,` in the string\n  - Cuts the string at those commas\n  - Returns an array of the resulting substrings\n\nExample behavior:\n\n```js\nparseCsvLine(\"a,b,c\");           // [\"a\", \"b\", \"c\"]\nparseCsvLine(\"1,2,3\");           // [\"1\", \"2\", \"3\"]\nparseCsvLine(\"a,,c\");            // [\"a\", \"\", \"c\"] (empty field in the middle)\n```\n\nLimitations (by design of this function):\n\n- It does not handle quoted CSV fields (e.g. `\"a,b\"` as a single field).\n- It does not trim whitespace around values.\n- It does not handle escaped quotes or commas inside quotes.\n\nSo in short: it’s a bare-bones CSV line splitter that treats every comma as a separator and returns the resulting pieces in an array.",
